34:44.149 --> 34:49.087 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: On Capitol Hill
today, a group
of top senators unveiled a
bipartisan bill

34:49.120 --> 34:52.223 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
to reform the nation's criminal
justice system.

34:52.257 --> 34:57.162 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
Among other things, the
legislation would
reduce prison sentences for some
nonviolent

34:57.195 --> 35:03.368 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
drug offenders, and create
programs to help
offenders reenter society. The
move comes

35:03.401 --> 35:09.507 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at the same time the Obama
administration
is pushing a series of criminal
justice initiatives.

35:09.541 --> 35:14.779 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Spearheading that effort is
Deputy Attorney
General Sally Yates, who joins
us now.

35:14.813 --> 35:16.614 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Deputy Attorney General Yates,
thank you for
being with us.

35:16.648 --> 35:18.416 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
SALLY YATES, U.S. Deputy
Attorney General:
Well, thank you for having me.

35:18.450 --> 35:22.153 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, tell us what
the thrust
of the administration's criminal
justice reform

35:22.187 --> 35:23.655 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
efforts are. What are you trying
to fix?

35:23.688 --> 35:26.291 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
SALLY YATES: Well, we're trying
to accomplish
a number of things.

35:26.324 --> 35:30.028 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
First, with the sentencing
reform bill, we're
really trying to bring
proportionality back

35:30.061 --> 35:35.000 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to sentencing, and specifically
for lower-level
nonviolent drug offenders. And
then with our

35:35.033 --> 35:39.304 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Reentry Week this week, we're
really trying
to highlight the importance of
assuring that

35:39.337 --> 35:43.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
those who are returning from
prison have just
those basic tools they need in
order to be

35:43.908 --> 35:45.610 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
able to be successful.

35:45.643 --> 35:48.580 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, what are some
examples
of that? What are some things
that they need

35:48.613 --> 35:50.782 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
that they aren't getting right
now, most of
them?

35:50.815 --> 35:54.886 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALLY YATES: Well, just imagine
right now
that you're leaving prison. You
may or may

35:54.919 --> 35:59.858 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
not have a family to go back to.
Particularly
if you were incarcerated a long
way from where

35:59.891 --> 36:04.562 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
your family lives, your wife may
have divorced
you at this point, so you may or
may not have

36:04.596 --> 36:06.364 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
a family to go back to.

36:06.398 --> 36:09.701 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And you may or may not have had
a chance to
stay in touch with your children
during this

36:09.734 --> 36:14.539 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
time as well. It's expensive for
people to
travel. So, you have got to find
a place to

36:14.572 --> 36:19.844 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
live. Public housing is
difficult. Some public
housing operations will not
allow convicted

36:19.878 --> 36:25.717 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
felons. Then you have got to
find a job. And
finding a job is really
difficult at all right

36:25.750 --> 36:29.754 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
now, but just imagine if you
have to add convicted
felon to your resume.

36:29.788 --> 36:34.359 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Now, just to be
clear, you're
working just on prisoners in the
federal system?

36:34.392 --> 36:36.094 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
Is that right?

36:36.127 --> 36:39.097 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALLY YATES: Well, we're looking
at both.
We're trying to help both
prisoners that are

36:39.130 --> 36:43.068 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
leaving the Federal Bureau of
Prisons, but
also working through our grant
program with

36:43.101 --> 36:44.569 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
state facilities as well.

36:44.602 --> 36:46.905 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: So, it's a big
job.

36:46.938 --> 36:48.440 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SALLY YATES: Yes.

36:48.473 --> 36:49.674 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I mean, we're
talking a lot
of prisoners around the country.

36:49.707 --> 36:51.476 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
SALLY YATES: Yes.

36:51.509 --> 36:54.746 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: You said this
week, I believe,
our criminal justice system is
not equipped

36:54.779 --> 36:58.383 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
