prisons will only count those
people that

38:33.578 --> 38:37.782 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are so mentally ill that they
are a danger
to themselves or others while
they're in a

38:37.815 --> 38:39.484 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
prison setting.

38:39.517 --> 38:43.555 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
And that doesn't really
necessarily capture
the full scope of mental health
issues.

38:43.588 --> 38:48.159 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Do you feel you
can make progress?
You mentioned working with
police, with corrections

38:48.193 --> 38:53.965 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
officers. How do you make
progress in that
arena? Again, you're talking
about individuals

38:53.998 --> 38:57.101 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
across the country in many
different settings,
local, state and federal.

38:57.135 --> 39:00.505 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
SALLY YATES: Well, one of the
things that
we have done is started training
crisis response

39:00.538 --> 39:03.741 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
teams for local law enforcement
agencies.

39:03.775 --> 39:08.012 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And that's a group of law
enforcement officers
